But let's touch on the story.

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:33.350
Let's think for a
moment of story and film

00:27:33.350 --> 00:27:35.230
as a dense atom of stuff.

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:38.340
And when you look at
this atom, you get it.

00:27:38.340 --> 00:27:41.270
You see everything.

00:27:41.270 --> 00:27:42.930
Now imagine that atom exploding.

00:27:45.571 --> 00:27:48.070
That color and that light and
the emotion in the characters,

00:27:48.070 --> 00:27:49.570
it's all over the place.

00:27:49.570 --> 00:27:52.100
And that's VR.

00:27:52.100 --> 00:27:54.530
And story has always been
a way of transporting you

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:56.760
to another place
or time or world.

00:27:56.760 --> 00:27:58.960
But the fundamental
nature of VR is presence.

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:00.570
There's no once
upon a time anymore.

00:28:00.570 --> 00:28:02.130
There's no in a world.

00:28:02.130 --> 00:28:03.780
You're there.

00:28:03.780 --> 00:28:05.530
And the story emerges
from when you do

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:06.910
or what you do
when you're there.

00:28:06.910 --> 00:28:09.230
And it's a result
of your existence.

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:13.400
You as a visitor are
now the storyteller.

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:17.340
And our job as creators is this.

00:28:22.946 --> 00:28:24.320
Now in order to
do this, we still

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:28.380
need a language so that
we can, at the very least,

00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:29.420
make sense of it all.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:32.570
And in retrospect, cinema
has had a hundred years

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:35.810
to deal with this, to be able
to come up with this language

00:28:35.810 --> 00:28:39.722
where from story
sort of emerged.

00:28:39.722 --> 00:28:41.180
And there's a lot
of unknowns here,

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:43.890
but we are pretty excited
about the language we've

00:28:43.890 --> 00:28:47.030
been able to discover so far.

00:28:47.030 --> 00:28:49.220
And we think it's a really
great place to start.

